  <static seed="1472" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/SolveLinearEquations/SolveLinearEquationParentheses160.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {3\mathopen{}\left(q+5\right)-7\mathopen{}\left(q-8\right)}={55}  }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="31" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\{4\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
3(q +5) -7(q-8)       \amp = 55 \\
3(q +5) +(-7)(q+(-8)) \amp = 55 \\
3q +3 \cdot 5 +(-7) \cdot q +(-7) \cdot (-8) \amp = 55 \\
3q +15 -7q +56 \amp = 55 \\
3q -7q +15+56 \amp = 55 \\
      -4q +71 \amp = 55 \\
      -4q +71\mathbf{{}-71} \amp = 55\mathbf{{}-71} \\
      -4q             \amp = -16 \\
      \frac{-4q}{-4} \amp = \frac{-16}{-4} \\
      q                      \amp = 4
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The solution to this equation is <m>4</m>. To stress that this is a value assigned to <m>q</m>, some report <m>q = 4</m>. We can also say that the solution set is <m>\{4\}</m>, or that <m>q\in\left\{4\right\}</m>. If we substitute <m>4</m> in for <m>q</m> in the original equation <m>3\mathopen{}\left(q+5\right)-7\mathopen{}\left(q-8\right)=55</m>, the equation will be true. Please check this on your own; it is an important habit.</p>
</solution>
